‎\begin{abstract}‎


‎An electromagnetic medium with varying refractive index can resemble a geometrical analogy with an arbitrary curved space-time \cite{leonhardt2006general}‎
‎The impedance-match condition for the medium is considered as a necessary factor that makes the geometrical analogy exact and induces the space-time metric in the dielectric medium‎. 
‎In this paper‎, ‎we show that a non-impedance-matched medium with a varying optical axis can resemble a non-trivial optical metric‎.
‎Before that‎, ‎we first extend the analogy of a curved space to birefringent media which is not impedance-matched‎. ‎As a result we show there is two different metric associated to each polarization of the light field in a birefringent medium‎.
‎Farther on‎, ‎we study the conditions that make the analogy between curved space-time and a medium with a varying optical axis‎. 
‎Extension of  the transformation optics to the media with optical axis profile might ease some fabrication cumbersome‎, ‎as impedance-matched materials are rare in nature‎. ‎Therefore‎, ‎it provides more achievable means to control the light trajectory in the novel optical devices such as invisibility cloaks‎. 
‎\end{abstract}‎

